European inflation slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is due first to the dizzying growth in the price of food products.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 eurozone countries, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - the Luxembourg-based Office for Union Statistics announced.
Official forecasts only gave 3 percent as likely, the Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the core interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and the reduction in forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "we must negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
3.3 percent inflation, recorded in Germany, broke the 12-year record, while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation skyrocketed in the eurozone as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat quotations increased by 88 per cent and the quotation of soybeans also reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold by almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will fall to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 per cent in the next 3 to 4 months, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice during the 2008 year.
