In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This anus has been recorded in hospitals several thousand infections caused first by the improper application of antibiotics.
Hygiene circumstances in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and staff overload do not favor infection control - says the department doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a contagion with MRSA has been diagnosed in the trauma department of the Hospital János.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of the antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital early in the year.
A wounded man from a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA contagion and since then no major surgical intervention has been performed due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistible agents have been registered in the Nosocomialis Surveillance System of the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said, a medical officer-CED of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that hospitals have surely recorded this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents, of the rest no information is available.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. the methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of humans carry the bacterium of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is over-exaggeratedly or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics, become highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly spread in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as infections of wounds or septicaemia in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to the elderly or to low-weight people.
According to the doctor-director of János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent, said Tibor Nyulasi, where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff care for them in rubber gloves and masks and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to check the presence of MRSA in their body, but this cannot even prevent infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples.
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and contagion with multiresist pathogens - says Karolina B.r.cz.
Because this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the sick who carry MRSA in their body.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient, said the doctor-scar department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes rigorous tasks for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological pictures.
It is necessary to insist that antibiotic therapy be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of street patients or in basic care - said Karolina B.r.cz.
It saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, the washing of the hands, the use of rubber gloves and masks are a very important role, however also in this sense there are considerable faults in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by transmission by droplets and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital wards are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated for at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - added Karolina B.r.cz - that in hospitals of less favourable economic situation it is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater probability for the infection.
In the opinion of Karolina B.r.cz, where appropriate preventive measures are met, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen may be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of contagion with MRSA is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is being fought.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The programme appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
