400 million euros more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed on Friday in Budapest three credit-limit agreements worth a total of 400 million euros to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget projects for transport and environmental protection projects, which will be carried out from the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement worth 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The credit contract of EUR 150 million is also allocated to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective of Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken at a later date, when the credit agreement is extended.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will mainly be used for the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the issue of the construction of the 4th Metro line.
The agreement was reached that by the time Hungary finalizes with the EU the details of Metro's funding, they will again address the issue that whether or not the original contract is necessary and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the appropriations is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging a fee for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
