Fodor and the six for hundreds of Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the expert level will be concluded on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration negotiations on the international climate regime will continue after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Road Map available to the post-mission reduction period efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
At present, lively discussions are being held on the issue between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the 1990 situation, until 2020, the emission of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is that whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
Agreement was also reached on aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF)," writes the "Piac és Profit."
Six for hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to preserve its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister said the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent to the 1990 level, whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed and is prepared to decline by up to 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Galbor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed themselves to a reduction by 5.2 per cent, among which the then 15 EU Member States committed themselves to achieving an 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce with 6 per cent the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect from 1985 to 87, which our country will fulfil - the press release of the Ministry of the Environment is quoted as saying.
Much is at stake in Balí, since in two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments made in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international UN scientific association dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and could not prevent an increase of more than 2oC in the Earth's average temperature, a fact that scientists say would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video dealer post recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operating body, then sent to London to be charged to the internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings of air force soldiers who have been loaded this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "prosecutor headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Community of British Nations (Commonwealth Office) and multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the Ministry of Defence's view they also serve to present to the public the real target of the British army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television stations of recruitment - he told the BBC the defence expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'etre of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans set up a video game
The army also cares about the fact that, in addition to the renowned and censored recordings, the distributor also features amateur videos, for example about the death of soldiers: in the propaganda film "official," a little hypocritical, the officers speak at the maximum of losses, without presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in actual operations have been uploaded from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently seizing this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different way for recruiting with free downloadable shooting video games called America's Army, where in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can get right instead of the soldiers.
