After more than 60 years of confidentiality, Bad Arolsen's Nazi archives, describing the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored over 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so farable only in a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his beneficiaries.
The eleven states responsible for their management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them up to searchers and historians.
Since the process of ratifying this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow for searches "particularly on the displacements of the prison workers, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, opposed the public's opening of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after war for a practical purpose: to find the countrymen deported or subjected in compulsory work and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their detention, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are dealing with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Search on Anti-Semitism at the Technische University in Berlin, said in 2006.
