Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which entered into force 1 November
Parallel to its parliamentary process, which ended today with the vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated into the bill in the Senate, the Government has submitted to a public hearing the regulations that will develop the new law, with the aim of getting the two into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulation in order to ensure the protection of investors and to regulate in detail the activity of the entities so that the markets function efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves the modernization of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and encouraging cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new regulations will make it possible to provide financial advisory services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services firm (ESIS), financial advisory firms (FIA), which joins securities companies, securities agencies and holding companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the implementation of transactions on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are joined by multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment firms to disclose on the market information on the key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and forms of risk management and requires them to keep track of all transactions they carry out, in order to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
In his passage through the Congressional Economics Committee, several amendments were incorporated, among which he highlights that securitised debts are considered a "complex" financial instrument given its high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated by what happened to the debt of high-risk US mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was taken to legally delimit the functions that can be carried out by graduates in Economics and Business 30 years after the adoption in 1977 of the royal decree delimiting the professional functions reserved for economists.
