Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the American credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is natural for some dorsal fins to be thrilled around.
Today that the American housing market is in crisis, predators have their eyes on the country's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses can reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis spreads other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of contagion are already seen.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been repaid or are more than 30 days late respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken 1.4 million charges in its American consumer finance business, in part because of the weakness of card borrowers.
However, it is too early for panic.
Lateness and crime are at low levels.
According to Moody's, a rating agency, the third quarter of the crime rate of 3.89% was almost one percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in American law on people's bankruptcy (2005) led to a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a big loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore late payment) would be growing again, or conditions for borrowers may have worsened.
The industry also reports solid payment rates, which show how much of their debts consumers pay each month.
And trust in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty strong, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emission volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of infection of the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to load credit card debts now that credit institutions are running.
But credit card issuers look more at the flow of liquidity than active securities, so falling prices don't necessarily trigger a change in borrowers' creditor capacity.
They can even work to overtake the issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue to write off the mortgage decline if properties are worth less than the value of the loan; and as a result, payment of the card's debt rises on the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions for mortgage lenders, changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That in theory should reduce the risk of rapid asset challenge.
"We're not going to wake up one day and reassess all the loans," says Gary Perlin, Capital One's finance chief.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If house prices are lower and a credit crunch push America into recession, the industry is undoubtedly facing a more severe future.
You have to keep watching those dorsal fins.
