Venus: twin brother of Earth.
Despite its atmosphere not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had a suspicion that there could be rays on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays fall from a height of 54 kilometers of one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles tells the scientific journal "Nature."
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: storms may have provoked reactions in the ocean that, on the other hand, would have given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not: if there was ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500oC recur on the surface, oscilling in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Possibly, Venus is a "diabolical" twin from Earth, but he's still a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so Earth-like for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus' research.
The latest results of the research to be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to the researchers, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with the Earth than we had assumed," reports ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by the fastest rotating clouds.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost as large.
This planet also called dawn star or evening star orbits around the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and with its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not resemble much Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets there had been agglomerated water on Earth that remained in the oceans, but in Venus it was dissected in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, in Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
