Rebel soldiers surrender in Manila.
Rebel soldiers who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila have surrendered in the Philippines and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The ringleader Antonio Trillanes, who reproaches the president for corruption and electoral fraud, told a reporter that he could not answer for shedding blood.
Soldiers loyal to the government had raided the hotel using tear gas.
Nearly two hundred soldiers have been entrenched in the building for a few hours.
Nearly half of them, including Trillanes, had a trial on Thursday for having attempted a coup in 2003 that ended with a failure.
He took advantage of the negotiations, so suddenly he could deposit himself with about 30 supporters.
Evidently the military police who had to watch him had gone into their ranks and followed his mutiny.
They entered the hotel "Peninsula" and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government troops blocked the neighborhood around the Noble Hotel.
The president called for an urgent session of the Security Cabinet.
Norbert Gonzales, the national security adviser, condemned the soldiers' behavior.
"People are fed up," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to move on to our ranks."
Gen. Danilo Lim, who previously ran the elite Scout Reangers troop, said the other military troops soon wanted to continue the march.
Major government critics on Thursday called for a large demonstration against the president.
For months his government has been rebuked for corruption.
In 2003, Manila's financial district was a place that attracted all the attention from the mutiny that was attempted against Arroyo.
The uprising failed after about 24 hours after the army wanted to take part.
Since 1986 in the Philippines there have been at least seven coup attempts against the democratically elected government.
